### Task 2: Prioritize workloads for migration based on value (Read-Only)

Prioritizing workloads for migration based on value in an Azure Migrate project means deciding which applications or servers to move first to get maximum benefit while minimizing risk and cost, instead of migrating everything at once.

This approach evaluates workloads using two key factors: business value and technical feasibility. Business value focuses on how important a workload is—such as systems that impact revenue, customer experience, or core operations. Migrating these early can improve performance, scalability, and reduce costs, especially for workloads that are expensive to maintain on-premises. Security and compliance requirements also increase a workload’s priority, as Azure provides strong built-in protections.

At the same time, technical feasibility ensures the migration is smooth. Some workloads are simple and easy to move, while others are complex, dependent on multiple systems, or built on legacy technologies. Tools in Azure Migrate, such as dependency mapping and readiness assessments, help identify which workloads can be migrated quickly and which need more planning.

In practice, organizations usually start with workloads that are high in value and low in complexity to achieve quick wins. More complex and critical systems are migrated later in a controlled manner, while low-value or outdated workloads may be postponed or retired.

Overall, this strategy helps organizations make smart, data-driven decisions, ensuring faster benefits, reduced risks, and a more efficient cloud migration journey.

